<TITLE> Nepal Maoists upset with PM over army integration </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 KATHMANDU, Jan 9 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Nepal's former Maoist rebels criticised Prime Minister Girija Prasad Koirala on Wednesday for refusing to integrate thousands of ex-guerrillas into the national army, in a sign of fresh political tension. About 31,000 former Maoist fighters housed in the United Nations-monitored camps await integration under a peace pact that brought the Maoists into the political mainstream. But Koirala was quoted in the media as saying that he opposed integrating the "politicised" fighters into the Nepal Army. The premier was reported to have suggested alternatives such as setting up a security force for companies and industries. Senior Maoist leader Baburam Bhattarai dismissed Koirala's comments, made on Tuesday, as "irresponsible" and said their fighters must be integrated into the national army. "It is really disturbing. We are very serious about it," Bhattarai said. Officials say a joint commission is expected to be set up to work out plans to integrate the former rebel fighters. In December, the Nepali parliament passed a motion to abolish the monarchy after elections, expected to be held before April 12 for a constituent assembly, in a deal with the Maoists who were insisting on an immediate declaration of a republic. That decision ended months of political deadlock between the government and the Maoists, who returned to the cabinet last month to move forward the peace deal that ended their civil war against the monarchy. The premier's refusal to take ex-guerrillas into the army "is against the comprehensive peace agreement" signed in 2006, Bhattarai said. The insurgency, which began in 1996, cost more than 13,000 lives and hit the aid- and tourism-dependent economy of Nepal, among the world's poorest countri
